  "reasoning": "Reasoning outline (concise):\n1) Manager implies exactly one spy. Examine Zane's statement: 'I am a knave.' If Zane were a knight, this would be false (a knight cannot claim to be a knave). If Zane were a knave, the statement would be true (he would be saying 'I am a knave'), but knaves always lie, so that cannot happen. Therefore Zane must be the spy. This also fixes the spy count to exactly one.\n2) With one spy fixed as Zane, Peter cannot be the spy. Peter's statement asserts that not all five share the same role. Given one spy exists, it is indeed impossible for all five to have the same role, so Peter's statement is true. Hence Peter is a knight.\n3) Kate says: 'Peter is lying.' Since Peter is a knight (truthful), Kate's statement is false. Therefore Kate is a knave.\n4) Olivia's statement asserts a compound truth about two sub-statements: (1) the number of truth-tellers among Kate, Peter, Zane is even; (2) all are knaves. Evaluate: (2) is false because Peter is a knight. For (1), Kate is knave (lying), Peter is knight (truthful), Zane is spy (his own statement 'I am a knave' is false). Thus among Kate, Peter, Zane, there is exactly one truth-teller (Peter), so the number is 1 (odd), making (1) false. Since both (1) and (2) are false, Olivia's claim that exactly one of them is true is false. Therefore Olivia is a knave.\n5) Noah states: 'Peter and Zane have the same role.' Peter is a knight, Zane is a spy; their roles differ, so this statement is false. Hence Noah is a knave.\nConclusion: Peter is the knight, Zane is the spy, and Kate, Olivia, Noah are knaves. This satisfies the manager's hint of exactly one spy and is logically consistent with all statements."
